@CarmineTirone @giacastyle That's the difference between trading and investing.

Traders are looking for gaps in the short term.

Investors are looking for gaps in the long term.

@Saltyjustino Collabland and snapshots are totally different.

Snapshots record blockchain state at a point in time and can be used for airdrops, voting, and tons of other stuff.

Collabland just verifies that you control a certain wallet to discord.

@BitcoinDaddy69 @crysyphus I tend not to recommend this because of my "simple" principle.

You now have two single points of failure, if either relative loses it or you're unable to reach them to get it you do not have a valid backup.

This can work, but for most I don't think it's a good option.

@moses23__ @opensea @BoredApeYC Here's my best guess from looking at the TXN:

First, you accidentally offered 70ETH on this mutant.

Second, an arbitrage bot noticed this and in a single transaction bought it at the market price and accepted your 70WETH offer making a ~43ETH profit after fees and the bribe.

@d_fins I would just very very carefully verify that the seed in your wallet matches your backup.

Or, if you are getting a second hardware wallet for an additional backup if the addresses match when you restore that wallet you're fine.

You just want to be sure that your backup is good.

@sssvenky @CRYPTO_TAG @cryptosteel Yep, looks very similar.

I'm only mentioning stuff I've personally used since I don't want to recommend anything that I can't vouch for.

It's not obvious from my quick look at their site. What keeps the letters from getting rearranged?

@fasteddiegloor @1saadnation @BoredApeYC Connecting a wallet is just a privacy concern as the website can associate that IP address with that wallet address.

There's pretty much no security risk with just connecting your wallet to anything.

Signing something is required to expose yourself to malicious contracts.
